deck_excerpt: The third most current version of my Dark Magician deck. After the failure of trying to integrate Lair of Darkness cards, I decided to keep it straigh
deck_description: The third most current version of my Dark Magician deck. After the failure of trying to integrate Lair of Darkness cards, I decided to keep it straight DM and add a little more draw power to the deck itself.  The Eye of Timaeus is a good card and all, but it is a brick that has a lot of potential. So I replaced it with the Keeper of Dragon Magic to build up the number of monsters in this deck that can be normal summoned. Keeper of Dragon Magic and Polymerization can be swapped with the Eye of Timaeus to lower card count and be more direct.  I feel like Torrential Tribute can really do good with Eternal Soul protecting DM. But I don't like the fact that I can still risk losing my cards. So I added 2x Drowning Mirror Force and 2x Mirror Force to the extra deck to be flexible in the event that torrential tribute is not helping. Battle Fader and Scapegoat are the Plan C for this to get a mini-wall out there for linking.  Dark Illusion is a great card IMO that protects almost all your monsters and can even work on your opponent's monsters to stop an effect. I feel it is a hidden gem that isn't known yet for DM. Dark Horizon is in the same boat but is hesitant if it wants to stay or not. It is very good for special summoning any of the Dark Spellcasters, depending on how screwed you are but you have to take the damage in order to use it. Dark Horizon could be very useful for getting out Apprentice Illusion Magician and get DM to your hand or even getting the DM out instead. Dark Illusion and Dark Horizon were meant to be swapped out with each other but could be together for the best coverage.  2x Eternal Souls. I find that 3x is too risky to run and that I will brick more often.  1x Dark Magic Attack for that quick removal of the back row.  Cosmo Brain is the card that I get questioned on. I like that it can become stronger than DM by discarding DM to the GY by 400 ATK and be able to still bring out the DM from hand or deck. Another hidden gem that is well known.  Mana Dragon Zirnitron, another situation like Dark Horizon, is a great card that can bring back Eternal Soul and start up DM domination. The problem I have is it is a possible brick. You have to hope your opponent will make your spell/trap card leave the field to become viable. Possible Side Deck but is up to the player.  Upstart Golbin and the Spellbooks for that draw power. I was thinking of running Wind Witches but feel that Wind Witches could be separated from DM since how good it is by itself.

deck_excerpt: - Can both aggro and control the game - Elemental HERO Shining Flare Wingman - As consistent as superheroes get
deck_description: Rating: 6/10 Uh, Treetop, this is pretty much the same Hero deck as last metagame. Yes. I know. It's great. Have you seen it? It's also been slightly more optimized since then. This deck can easily summon Elemental HERO Shining Flare Wingman. It can also pretty much any other HERO Fusion if you play the fusion requirements, but I went for a more consistent build. You can easily throw Elemental HERO Plasma Vice into this particular build because of Sparkman. Strengths: - Tonnes of backrow, largely all chainable - Extremely consistent - Mad resource loops through Stratos, Vyon, Mist, Pot of Avarice - Power plays through miracle fusion - Summon the sickest HERO fusions - Very aggro Weakness: - Fights slowly through negation - Losing your only playstarter makes it a tough game to win - Shinging Flare Wingman etc requires some bricks - Called by the Grave on shadow mist hurts a lot (It's also being played a lot more in the current metagame) Trinities: - 2nd Copy of Elemental HERO Shadow Mist - 2nd Copy of Reinforcement of the Army - 3rd Copy of Reinforcement of the Army - Elemental HERO Honest Neos (Semi-Forbidden) Interactions of note: - Miracle Fusion on Versago the Destroyer and Elemental HERO Sparkman - Vision HERO Vyon sends Elemental HERO Shadow Mist to search for any HERO and Polymerization, which makes any Attribute HERO Fusion. - Mask Change or Form Change on Elemental HERO Absolute Zero into Masked HERO Acid - Tour Guide from the Underworld searches Versago the Destroyer - Armageddon Knight, Future Fusion, Lavalval Chain, or Foolish Burial sending Shaddoll Dragon (Instead of the usual Shadow Mist) - Elemental HERO Stratos plus revival is 6800 damage through Elemental HERO Honest Neos. Any 1200+ATK HERO in hand is a 2 card OTK. - Elemental HERO Absolute Zero gains its effect even when sent to the GY as Link material.
Dark Law Turbo

I know how much you guys really like my Trickstar deck profiles since they get so many views so I decided to make another one for 2019! The new Trickstar monster, Trickstar Corobane is a searchable Honest for Trickstars that boosts the decks potential even more than before. The new Pot of Extravagance also helps push this decks limits even further since Trickstars don't really use their extra deck for the most part except with Scapegoat and now that Scapegoat is at 1 because of the banlist, it isn't a really great card anymore being a 1 of. I know you guys may be thinking why two Extravagance and two Pot of Desires? Well it's because when playtesting I didn't see both a Desires and an Extravagance in most of my opening hands. If you don't like Desires you could switch it out to two Pot of Duality, but I like two Desires and two Extravagance. This deck definitely wants to go first every time possible. Having three Gozen Match and all the Solemns really hurts your opponent and lets you otk fast turn three when you go first. Plus the Trickstar Reincarnation and Droll & Lock Bird combo is still viable so going first three Reincarnation and three Droll is a must in the main deck. Overall this deck is really solid and hardly ever bricks, at least from my experience whenever I was making it from scratch and testing it. A lot of the side deck I dedicated to Thunder Dragons since it is a huge threat to Trickstars. The reason for Super Polymerization in the side deck is to bring out Predaplant Dragostapelia using your opponents Thunder Dragon monsters going second since Dragostapelia requires a fusion monster (Colossus or Titan) plus another dark monster (any Thunder Dragon monster) and they cannot respond to it because Super Poly says they cannot respond to the cards effect. I really hope you all enjoy the deck and stick around for more!

deck_name: Salamangreat Deck (TCG Only/ April Ban List 2019)
deck_excerpt: Basic build for a salamangreat deck
deck_description:
Basic build for anyone who wants to run a salamangreat deck using his Structure deck cards, with some few additions.

Tips Vs. METAs

  1. For Mirrors against others salas, substitute Effect Veiler (Or any other hand trap you are using) to put 2 Ghost Reaper & Winter Cherries to banish Salamamgreat Sunlight Wolf or Miragestallio from your opponent's Extra Deck. Then, put 3 D.D Crown in place of the 3rd Veiler, Beat Bison and Crusadia Reclusia. You can remove 1 of each trap and Transcode Talker to put 2 Super-Poly and World Chalice Guardragon Almarduk
  2. If you are up against Thunder Dragons, use Update Jammer + Borreload Dragon combo (If you have), to steal your oponnent Thunder Dragons. This also works with Borrelsword to attack 4 times with a huge attack. You can remove 1 of each trap and Transcode Talker to put 2 Super-Poly and Starving Venom Fusion Dragon
  3. Against Skystriker, make sure you have Transcode Talker and a Salamangreat Link monster linked to it. They will be protected against all skystriker spells that targets, then you can reduce his effectviness slowly using Salamangreat Roar and Rage. D.D. Crown is really effective now, banish Kagari asap. If you have Denko Sekka, put it as well.
  https://youtu.be/fTPWPxRJ5AM

Trey

Trey, known as III in the Japanese version, Three in the Italian version, and born Michael Arclight, is a character appearing in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ZEXAL anime. He has a gentle personality and loves his family. Like his brothers, he swears revenge on Dr. Faker, though he cares more about the family's welfare, eventually putting his faith to save them in his friend Yuma Tsukumo.

Chronomaly

"Chronomaly", known as "OOPArts" (Ōpātsu or Opacheu) in Japan or Korea, is an archetype of monsters used by Trey in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ZEXAL anime. Most of their Attributes are either EARTH or LIGHT, while most of their Types are either Machine or Rock. Their effects support each other well, enabling quick swarming and Xyz Summons of Rank 5 Xyz Monsters, particularly through the LIGHT monsters.

Geargia

 

Playing Style

All 8 "Geargia" monsters focus heavily on searching out each other, swarming the field in the process and Summoning Rank 3 and 4 Xyz Monsters, especially their ace cards, "Geargiagear Gigant XG" and "Gear Gigant X". Each monster has a different effect to search out cards: "Geargiano" Special Summons any Level 4 Machine monster from the Graveyard by Tributing itself, meaning that the card can be good to support other archetypes; "Geargiano Mk-II" can do the same as "Geargiano", but only with "Geargia" monsters, however it can also Special Summon the monster from the hand; "Geargiano Mk-III" do the same as "Geargiano Mk-II", but only if it is Special Summoned by the effect of a "Geargia" card; "Geargiarmor" search any "Geargia" from the Deck each time it is flipped face-up and is a solid wall with 1900 DEF; "Geargiaccelerator" helps to swarm the field, as it can Special Summon itself from your hand and has the bonus effect of adding another Geargia from your Graveyard to your hand when it goes to the Graveyard; "Geargiarsenal" can Tribute itself to Special Summon any "Geargia" from your Deck and also gains 200 ATK for each "Geargia" you control, even itself; "Geargiattacker" destroys Spell/Trap Cards on the field, up to the number of "Geargia" monsters you control each time it is flipped face-up.

deck_excerpt: A fun deck that turbo out Azathot with Raidraptor !
deck_description:
The strategy is simple : Turboing out Cyber Dragon Infinity and Outer Entity Azathot on your very first turn ( Well, on the opponent's turn in Azathot's case ). It can usually go as follow :
  • Try to summon Wise Strix with at least one more Lvl4 monster on the field, preferably with Nest
  • Wise Strix effect, summon out Zephyros
  • Xyz summon Force Strix, detach Zephyros, search for Singing Lanius, special summon Singing Lanius
  • Set RUM Soul Shave Force with Wise Strix
  • Link summon PK of Rusty Bardiche with Wise Strix and Force Strix
  • Use Soul Shave Force to rank up in to CyDra Infinity
  • Make Time Thief Redoer ( Either by returning Nest to the hand to summon back Zephyros, or set the PK trap monster with Bardiche )
  • Activate Redoer, banish himself until the end phase
  • Set PK RUM ( You get 2 searches off one Bardiche, one from Bardiche himself and the other from Silent Boot )
  • During your opponent main phase 1, activate PK RUM on Redoer for Azathot
Occasionally you can also summon out Ultimate Falcon along with Azathot, and sometime you can replace Azathot entirely with V.F.D. which give a much better lock than Azathot.

World Chalice

https://youtu.be/L19tL7rwLSA

Playing Style

Being one of the first archetypes to focus on Link Summoning, the "World Chalice" archetype explores the intricacies of the newly-introduced mechanic. To that end, the archetype focuses on initiating multiple Link Summons in quick succession, all while promoting combos that extend the longevity of this style of play, namely through helping the controller amass more monsters in the hand or on the field to use as Link Materials. The archetype also encourages the controller carefully consider the placement of cards on their field, particularly by emphasizing the linking of Link Monsters with other monsters in order to gain boons via their effects.

The archetype's main strategy is the rapid amassing of Link Materials on the field to Link Summon Link Monsters, mainly by using Normal Monsters as a medium. To that end, several of its Main Deck monsters are Normal Monsters, namely "Beckoned by the World Chalice", "Chosen by the World Chalice", and "Crowned by the World Chalice", all of which possess different Levels, Attributes, and Types, and either 0 ATK or DEF. The archetype's Main Deck Effect Monsters are designed to further this strategy. The first effect of "World Chalice Guardragon" allows the controller to send it from the hand or field to the GY in order to negate the activation of a card that targets a linked monster and destroy it, thus offering protection to the controller from threats to the archetypes' Link Monsters. This also places "Guardragon" in the GY to enable its second effect, banishing it from the GY to Special Summon a Normal Monster from the GY to one of the controller's zones that a Link Monster points to. "Lee the World Chalice Fairy" enables the controller to add a "World Chalice" monster from their Deck to their hand if Normal or Special Summoned, assisting the player in providing monsters to Special Summon with the common effect of the archetype's Link Monsters. "Lee" also allows the controller to recover it from the GY to their hand if they send a monster from their hand or field to the GY. Both monsters have great synergy with each other as a result, given that the latter can place monsters in the GY in the process of recurring itself, which the former can then Special Summon for the controller to continue their combos.

Pierre the Gambler

Pierre the Gambler, known in Japan as Mitsuo ( Mitsuo) is Alexis Rhodes' childhood classmate and a world famous gambler, having mastered games from blackjack to poker. In primary school, Pierre would play games of chance with other students, always having them bet their prized possessions. After losing a game of Duel Monsters to Alexis, he steals her red hankerchief, which had been bet on the Duel. Years later, he arrives at Duel Academy where he asks Chancellor Sheppard and Vellian Crowler to let him duel Alexis. When they turned him down, he ended up taking out the Duel Academy security team that Chancellor Sheppard summoned until Alexis arrives agreeing to the duel. He finally duels with Alexis, but loses. In the end, it is revealed he actually has a crush on Alexis and returns the handkerchief to her. However, Alexis does not return these feelings and Pierre then leaves with Jaden Yuki trying to bid him farewell in the right way.

deck_excerpt: Silent Magician and Bamboo Sword Control
deck_description: This deck serves three main purposes: locking down your opponent by cutting off vital phases of his turn, manipulating monster effects to control the field (a favorite of mine being floating The Tricky into a Silent Magician with Silent Burning's Graveyard effect first turn to kill spells before they even have a chance), and attacking over your opponent's monsters for various qualities of damage output. Of all these effects, some of the most powerful are held by Cursed. Don't be afraid to equip one to an early monster, or to discard one with Tricky, as you can add any Bamboo card you might need to your deck. Also try to take advantage of the combo between Soul and Cursed, activating Soul to make use of it before adding it back to your hand to prevent destruction, and then immediately being able to attack directly to seal the effect.  Also, this deck obviously doesn't run any cards to replace SM when she gets destroyed by battle, so if you want to play it safe and don't want to run synchro monsters as a mandatory element, fire away with taking out Umbreacum and replacing it with SMLV8.

deck_name: Reversal Quiz FTK - Danger! Dark World Deck
deck_excerpt: An FTK deck using Reversal Quiz and Danger! cards
deck_description:
Deck Created By: Big Crunch (Deck Inspiration: Slash Draw FTK) Main Goal: To gather the 4 main cards that will accomplish the FTK and to thin out the deck until it only contains monster cards or one spell card (unless the combo stops). How to Accomplish: Use the monsters to swarm the field and also use the draw spell cards to thin the deck and add cards to hand. (Info Below) Monsters
  • Danger! Cards - Use to swarm the field (Especially with Dogman and Nessie) and thin out the deck. (Some monster can be Normal summoned if necessary)
  • Dr. Frankenderp - If Emergency Teleport is on hand, use the card and summon this card then activate the effect to draw a card. If not, Normal Summon or Special Summon using Saryuja. (You can only use the effect once)
  • Blackwing - Zephyros the Elite - Use it to return an important monster card or Temple of the Kings (Free Monster) if its on the graveyard. (You can only use the effect to Special Summon once) (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Blackwing - Steam the Cloak - Use it to summon tokens (Saryuja can help) and to help a bit on swarming. (You can tribute a card to Special Summon it from the Graveyard) (You can only Special Summon it once) (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Broww, Huntsman of Dark World - If discarded, a card is added (Extra monster to Normal Summon if necessary)
  • Shaddoll Beast - If discarded, a card is added (Only once though)
Draw Spells
  • Upstart Goblin - Hand neutral card (Helps with thinning)
  • Allure of Darkness - Hand neutral card (Helps with thinning and removing unecessary Dark cards)
  • Card Destruction - Card that replaces your entire hand with new cards (DON'T SEND THE 4 MAIN CARDS TO THE GRAVEYARD EVER!!!) (Use it if hand is bad, hand is filled with discard cards or when hand is filled with many cards) (Helps with thinning a lot if in a right moment)
  • The Beginning of the End - A +2 card when Graveyard is filled with Dark monsters (7+ Dark cards to be precise) (Helps with thinning and drawing) (Avoid using two at the same time unless the Graveyard is filled)
  • Into the Void - A situational Upstart Goblin (When you have 3+ cards in your hand, you can use it)
Other Card
  • Emergency Teleport - Use it on Frankenderp (If Frankenderp is already used, use it as a discard)
  After that, you can go to these Extra Deck cards
  •  Mecha Phantom Beast Dracossack - Basically, a mini Galaxy Tomahawk. Use it to swarm the field with tokens. (A mini Swarmer)
  • Saryuja Skull Dread - Use it to refill your hand with new cards and get rid unecessary ones. (Summon it using 4 monsters [most of the time] unless its really necessary)
  • Akashic Magician - Use it to return an important monster (Mostly Saryuja)
  • Wee Witch's Apprentice - A two arrowed Link monster that is good for having two Extra Deck monsters (Also a Dark monster)
  • Space Insulator - A Link monster that can use any monster for summon (Good when tokens are out) (Also a Dark monster)
  • LANphorhynchus - A Link monster that can use any monster for summon and also good for having two Extra Deck monsters (A good card?)
  • Link Spider - Good for token renaming (For Saryuja)
  Then, here are the card you need on the field at all times   Main Cards
  •  Reversal Quiz - if the setup is done, use this card to swap with your opponents life points
  • Temple of the Kings - use it to immediately activate the trap card
  • Wall of Revealing Light - use it to lower you life points as much as possible (but not 0)
  • Fuhma Shuriken - Set this on the field and after the setup is done, this will finish of the opponent (almost all of the time)
  The consistency of the can be improved, so you can adjust the deck as much as you want.

deck_excerpt: I've always thought, "What's the maximum board I can make with a]zombies?" and I recently thought, "What's the exact minimum you need to create a guar
deck_description:
What you want to do is set up 2-5 negations on your first turn to stop your opponent from doing the same or similar to you. You're gonna want to pay close attention to this next part. 3 card combo to end on 4(or 5) negates with zombie guardragon. Shiranui Solitaire + Mezuki + Wyverbuster
  1. Normal Solitaire, tribute and special Unizombie from deck
  2. Send Gozuki from deck to grave, banish Solitaire, special Mezuki from hand
  3. Link into Vampire Sucker. Banish Mezuki, summon Gozuki from grave. Vampire Sucker's eff: 1 draw so far
  4. Gozuki effect, send 2nd mezuki to grave. Link Vampire Sucker and Gozuki into Summon Sorceress
  5. Banish Uni-Zombie from grave, special Wyverbuster from hand in one of SS's zones. Summon Sorceress eff, summon Destrudo from deck
  6. Banish Mezuki to special Gozuki from graveyard, link all 4 monsters for Saryuja. Draw 4 and search Collapserpent with Wyverbuster effect. Priority cards are Rescue Ferret, Monster Reborn/World Legacy Succession, and Necroworld Banshee/Zombie World. Priority shuffles are your level 1 tuners. 5 draws so far, 3 shuffles
  7. If you have any monster in hand, Saryuja effect special summon them to a zone without a link arrow pointing to it.
  8. Special Collaserpent and link into Elpy to the right-most Saryuja zone with it. Elpy effect, special Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon
  9. REDMD effect, special Destrudo from grave, link REDMD and Destrudo into Agarpain in Saryuja's left-most zone. Agarpain effect Summon Crystal Wing in Saryuja's middle zone
  10. Link Saryuja, Agapain, Elpy, and the monster summoned with Saryuja's effect into your second Saryuja in the EMZ on the opposite side. Draw 4 with Saryuja. Shuffle 3 and special Rescue Ferret from your hand with Saryuja's effect. 9 draws so far, 6 shuffles
  11. Rescue Ferrect effect: Summon your 3rd Mezuki, any level 1 Earth tuner, and Glow-up Gloom. Destrudo effect from grave, target Mezuki If you have banshee in grave or zombie world in hand, activate zombie world
  12. Mezuki + level 1 earth tuner, synchro Naturia Beast. Banish Mezuki, special Gozuki for the final time from grave. Synchro F.A Dawn Dragster with Gozuki and Destrudo.
  13. Synchro Borreload Savage Dragon with F.A Dawn Dragster and Glow-up Gloom, equip Saryuja from grave. Activate Monster Reborn/World Legacy Succession to special F.A Dawn Dragster from grave. (If you have zombie world active, banish glow-up gloom and special Balerdroch from deck)
  14. End board: Saryuja pointing to FA Dawn Dragster, Borreload Savage Dragon, and Naturia Beast. With Crystal Wing on it's own.
  15. End turn. I honestly doubt any opponent waited for your entire combo to end before scooping.
If you opened Solitaire/Uni-Zombie and either Gozuki or Shinobi Necro and Mezuki: Send/Discard Shinobi to the gy, send Gozuki next, banish shinobi to special Mazuki from hand. Special Shinobi with it's effect, link mezuki + uni-zombie to make Vampire sucker, banish mezuki and special gozuki from gy. Draw and discard and draw and then continue the combo from there.

deck_excerpt: Spyral Warrior Extra Link Aqua Dolphin Turbo (Going First) (Post December 2019 Banlist)
deck_description: In my Pure Trickstar build for 2019 I asked you guys if you wanted a custom Spyral deck or something else, and it seems that you guys wanted the custom Spyral deck as the deck got both three likes AND a comment which is amazing! Thank you so much for telling me what deck content you guys want and for supporting me. Now I've been fooling around with the Warrior engine a little bit combined with Spyrals. These two go together very nicely since SPYRAL Super Agent is a Warrior type monster as well as SPYRAL Tough even though I decided to only put one Tough in the deck. You always want to go first with this deck if possible. A Warrior monster plus a Warrior extender or a Super Agent in your opening hand means you will be able to extra link your opponent if you are going first. Also the deck is crazy because I've made it so you can loop Neo-Spacian Aqua Dolphin's effect multiple times going first to take handtraps and monsters in general out of your opponent's hand so they can't play their next turn and will have to scoop. The way this works is once you summon Dolphin the first time and use it's effect, you can then use it for link material for Isolde and then bring it back out from the graveyard or banished pile with other extenders such as the equip spell, D.D.R, or Monster Reborn, etc... You can also use Isolde's effect to send four equip spells from your deck to grave in order to special summon Neo Space Connector which will allow you to use it's effect to send itself and special summon Dolphin from grave to use his effect again. The other combo to loop Dolphin's effect is using Divine Sword - Phoenix Blade in the graveyard to banish Dolphin and another Warrior monster and then use D.D.R to send the Divine Sword you just added to special summon Dolphin again. Then proceed to use Divine Sword again and banish two Warrior monsters and use Dolphin's effect to pitch Divine Sword to take another monster out of your opponent's hand. Another way to pull off this Divine Sword Dolphin combo is using Destrudo The Lost Dragon's Frisson to synchro into Power Tool Dragon and use its effect to force your opponent to choose the D.D.R from your deck, and add it to your hand. Then loop the Divine Sword and D.D.R and Dolphin. I've been able to win games on ygopro with just Dolphin's effect going first because I loop Dolphin four or five times and then they can't play because they don't have the monsters they need to go off into their combos in their hand anymore. The deck can brick sometimes, but I believe I have made it the as consistent as it can possibly be made. The brick ratio I would say isn't too high but sometimes it can happen. I will now explain how to extra link your opponent. Firstly, you need to summon two Warrior monsters and go into Isolde, Two Tales of The Noble Knights. Then use her effect to send four equip spells from deck to grave to special summon a Super Agent or Tough from deck, then you should be able to go into Summon Sorceress with Isolde and another Warrior monster besides Super Agent and use her effect to special summon another Super Agent or Tough and then use those two monsters to go into SPYRAL Double Helix. Then you can use Double Helix to special summon SPYRAL Master Plan and use her effect to add SPYRAL MISSION -  Rescue from your deck to hand. You can also use Dolphin's effect to send Rescue to grave as cost and use Rescue later. The next step is to go into Knightmare Unicorn using Summon Sorc, Double Helix and Master Plan. If you don't already have SPYRAL Resort on the field then go ahead and set a spell/trap you don't need from your hand facedown before you summon Unicorn, and use Master Plan's effect and Unicorn's effect to send Rescue to grave to shuffle that card you set back into the deck, or if you do have Resort on the field already then shuffle Resort back into the deck instead of a facedown spell/trap in your hand you don't need. Then use Rescue in grave to banish itself to special summon Master Plan back to use her effect to add another Rescue and go into Knightmare Mermaid using Unicorn and use it's effect to send that Rescue from hand to grave and special summon Knightmare Corruptor Iblee from the deck. And now you can link into Knightmare Cerberus using Master Plan and Iblee right under Mermaid. The idea is just to keep looping Rescue and the SPYRAL MISSION - Assault in the deck to keep special summoning Master Plan and/or other Spyral monsters from grave and use SPYRAL Quik-Fix to get SPYRAL GEAR - Big Red to loop Master Plan an addition time. At the end of all that special summon looping, end with Quik-Fix and use it to make Linkuriboh in the other link zone, completing the extra link. It will be impossible for your opponent to get over this unless they main Evenly Matched or Ra Sphere Mode which is unlikely. Games two and three its best to make Trigate Wizard and co-link it times three so you can negate their Evenly Matched if they try to use it on you during their following turn after you go first. You can even use Summon Sorc to special summon Quik-Fix from the deck after summoning Power Tool Dragon since Power Tool is a Machine type monster and so is Quik-Fix. I did consider going second as an option if you don't win the rps or dice roll while building this deck from scratch of course! That's why I added Crusadia Arboria to the deck as an extender, because not only is it a Warrior type monster and a free special summon, but it's a tuner which means you can go into Black Rose Dragon to wipe your opponent's board going second. I also added Brionac, Dragon of The Ice Barrier to deal with annoying boss monsters like Thunder Dragon Colossus. With Brionac's effect you can send Rescue or Assault from your hand to grave which is really helpful. You can also use Destrudo to go into Brionac or Black Rose Dragon which is really helpful or if you don't have it you can summon Arboria off Isolde's second effect! There's just so many cool combos I came up with while building this deck and overall it's a really fun deck to play and most of the time will win if you go first. I really hope you guys enjoy this deck, I put a lot of time and effort playtesting it for you guys just like I do every other custom deck I post.

deck_excerpt: A Deck for fans of Red Dragon Archfiend.
deck_description:
If you know Jack and the many tuners that he uses, this deck shouldn't be that hard to use. But before using it, read the combos and more below: Combos (To get Red Dragon Archfiend on Field): Red Resonator + Red Sprinter (Red Sprinter + Red Resonator works as well. Just make sure you control no monsters when using Red Sprinter first): Summon Red Resonator, then use it's effect to Special Summon Red Sprinter. Then use both to Synchro Summon Red Rising Dragon. Use Rising Dragon's effect to bring back Red Resonator. Then Synchro Summon again to become Red Dragon Archfiend. Any Level 2 Resonator + Red Warg: This one is easy. Summon any Level 2 Resonator (Force or Red Resonator), then you should be able to Special Summon Red Warg, which should then lead to Red Dragon Archfiend. Beyond Red Dragon Archfiend: Any Level 8 "Red Dragon Archfiend" + Chain Resonator + Any Level 3 Resonator: This deck contains two Level 12 Synchros. One requires the original Red Dragon Archfiend while another doesn't. The steps are the same. With a Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monster, summon Chain Resonator. Use it's effect to Special Summon a Level 3 Resonator (Clock or Dark). Then with there combined levels, tune them with a Red Dragon Archfiend to create either "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity" or if using the original Red Dragon Archfiend, you can go for "Red Nova Dragon". Red Rising Dragon + 2 Level 2 Resonators (Red or Force): I haven't tried this one, so I don't know if it will work, but you can try. You Synchro Summon Red Rising Dragon using the above method, then instead of going to Level 8, wait until you get another Level 2 Resonator (If it's in the Graveyard, cards like "Red Carpet" and "Resonator Engine" could work). Summon the 2nd Level 2 Resonator and you should get "Tyrant Red Dragon Archfiend". Red Rising Dragon + 2 Level 2 Resonators (Use 2nd Resonator after Synchro Summon with Red Rising): (Easier version of above) Summon a Level 8 red Dragon Archfiend Monster, then use the 2nd Level 2 Resonator to get "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Bane". Any Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monster + Chain Resonator (Don't need to use Chain's effect): With a Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro, summon Chain Tinker and bring out "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss".   NOTE:
  • If you noticed, I used one original Red Dragon Archfiend and used more of Hot. That's because the original's first effect kind of mocks me. How monsters that don't attack are destroyed isn't helpful. This may make summoning Red Nova Dragon hard. You can add two more copies of it if you want, this is just my opinion
 
  • The Continuous Trap "King Scarlet" can also be used with a Level 8 Red Dragon Archfiend Synchro Monster for "Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss"
 
  • I found "Synchro Cracker" to be very useful and fun to use. By sending a Synchro Monster you control to the Extra Deck, you can destroy all monsters your opponent controls that are weaker than the Synchro's ATK. Since a lot of cards in this deck have really high ATK power, you can use it to destroy almost all of your opponent's monsters (Like a King)
 
  • King's Synchro is also a good trap if you want to add
  That's all. Enjoy the Deck :)

Dark Scorpion

  "Dark Scorpion", known as "Black Scorpion" (Kurosasori) in Japan, is an archetype of DARK Warrior monsters who have Trigger Effects that activate when they inflict battle damage to their opponent, giving the controller a choice of two effects. The majority of these card effects disrupt the opponent's field, hand or Deck, with the exception of "Dark Scorpion - Meanae the Thorn" who instead searches out other "Dark Scorpion" cards. All members of this archetype are Level 3-4 monsters, except for the Level 5 "Dark Scorpion - Gorg the Strong". The "Dark Scorpions" have been featured on numerous Spell and Trap Cards. "Don Zaloog" and "Dark Scorpion Burglars" were introduced in Pharaonic Guardian, "Cliff" in Magician's Force, and the rest in Dark Crisis.

Playing style

The "Salmangreat" monsters have various effects related to battle and GY recursion. A common theme among many of their monsters is they work best when with another monster of the same name. The most simple and powerful example is "Salamangreat Gazelle" who sends any "Salamangreat" card from the Deck to the GY, and can also Special Summon itself from the hand if a "Salamangreat" monster is sent to the GY. Many of the archetype's effects also involve shuffling cards from the GY into the Deck and discarding cards, so manipulation of the GY successfully gives the Deck a lot of potential. A key part of the Deck's combos is "Salamangreat Sanctuary", which allows the player to use a "Salamangreat" with the same name as a monster being Link Summoned as the entire material. As with the lesser monsters, the boss monsters get stronger when Summoned using a monster with the same name, making "Sanctuary" the quickest and easiest way to open up the full potential of the Deck's Link monsters. It can be searched by "Salamangreat Balelynx" to increase consistency. The main win condition of many builds is to set up a "Salamangreat Violet Chimera" Summoned using another copy of itself, which basically guarantees an OTK if all its effects resolve. The other Extra Deck monsters are dedicated to supporting this strategy, or for supporting the Deck's recursion/battle effects. The Deck's Ritual Monster "Salamangreat Emerald Eagle" provides a finisher/alternate attacker that can clear all the opponent's Special Summoned monsters if Ritual Summoned using an "Emerald Eagle" the player controls, and can sacrifice unneeded Link Monsters to get over tough monsters while inflicting heavy Burn damage. As any modern Deck must, the Spell/Trap lineup of the Deck also has a heavy control element. "Salamangreat Roar" is a powerful Counter Trap Card that can negate any monster effect or Spell/Trap card while you control a "Salamangreat" Link Monster, that can Set itself from the GY when a "Salamangreat" is self-Link Summoned at the cost of banishing itself when it leaves the field. It can also be recovered by "Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf", who can also play a key role in grabbing "Fusion of Fire" or other key Spell/Trap cards. Many of these get stronger when a self-Summoned Salamangreat Link Monster is present, so maintaining and protecting a powerful monster like "Salamangreat Heatleo" can reap many rewards, even over a relatively short Duel. Finally, a key step in setting up these plays is "Salamangreat Miragestallio"

deck_excerpt: Deck list for Crimson Wind Academy's 100$ budget tournament.
deck_description: Honestly i'm not sure if it was worth running salamangreats now that i had to cut an ash blossom and my rivalries, but i don't have enough time to build and price a new deck and they're dumb anyways

Okay, so for those of you on a budget and don't want to make a dent on your wallet and still play Sky Strikers, either be because you like the artwork, how the deck plays or whatever the reason, I've come up with a super consistent decklist.  This deck can do everything a normal sky striker deck can do, except go crazy on card advantage(as no engage is present) and without stealing your opponent's Lady Debug.  And as such, this deck simply can't do a lot much with decks that go crazy on card advantage or with a great recovery.     I'll explain how without engage you can try to win your matchups and the general strategy of the deck.  First of: you have 8 of the best starters, which are: Raye, Hornet, ROTA and Formud Skipper. And you have 5 of the soft searchers, which will be a bit of RNG to get a Raye or Hornet from it, but some times it will work, and this is: Area Zero and Terraforming. Then you have Card Destruction and Reasoning, Card destruction after activated, you have around 70% chance of getting one of the 8starters and 50% chance of getting the the soft searchers. Reasoning is a lot of RNG, but in genereal most of the times people will declare 4 and your raye will be sent to the grave, that's not that bad, as the main reason reasoning is played here is, aside for dumping your grave with spells, you can get Raye(if they don't declare 4 and you excavate it) or get you Formud on field; if you get Veiler, if you have the field with you, target it and try to send to grave, if you don't, just link summon linkuriboh to free your main zone. And then you have other combos, like Field+TwinTwisters/JammingWaves/Multiroll. Also there's Foolish goods, if your hand don't have literally anything you can use to start your play, don't be afraid to dump metalfoes fusion, maybe that one draw might be your last one, or it may be a Raye.  Also, when the card Cynet Mining gets released on the TCG, your chance of opening one of the best starters goes to 82%, and this is more than the rate of opening Engage/Raye/Rota/Hornet on the actual Sky Striker deck.(If you, a pro Sky Striker player out there is reading this, think about Formud Skipper and Cynet Mining and see how it can increase the consistency of the deck :v)  Now for the Matchups:  Lair of Darkness AKA shit virus deck: you lose, unless they brick so so so so so hard.  Thunder Dragon: Haven't played much against them, you can't compete with their card advantage, tre best you can do is have your Shizuku and use Eagle Booster on her and try to survive each turn this way. Or you can side the Toon Cyber Chimeratech engine to at least get rid of the Titan they leave on the Extra Zone. Locking their of they grave with maybe Necrovalley could help, but then you're also locking yourself as well, so it's a mixed. Also I've sided 3 Eater of Millions just for problematic shit like Colossus, since you're just using 10 of the Sky Strikers link(triple Kagari, Hayate, Shizuku and 1 Kaina) you can just banish your other 5 to get rid of Colossus)  Altergeist: Playable and actually solely dependant on player's skills, Twin twisters, jamming waves, eaglebooster your stuff.  Salamangreat: If you go first, abosutely try to dump your Shark Cannon and set it, just banish Spinny if they try to summon that, or after they use Gazelle banish it so they won't recur it, tought banishing spiinny is preferable. Twin twisting their field also is great, as they can't do the better plays without it and they only run 1 of it mostly. Veilering Debug also completely stops their entire combo, unless they have spinny on hand, also the Skull meister is a great side deck against Salads. If you go second, bait that roar, just bait that roar and you're absolutely fine, if they rage you, Raye simply use her quick effect or if they rage a link, just get back Raye. Also the Segmental Dragon is great against this matchup as well, just grab yourself some spells in grave, summon shizuku to lower their attack and use his effect to destroy everything(try to banish Baillynx or force it) Skull Meister is also a good side against this deck.  Pendulum: Requires skill, but it's actually fairly fair.  Azathot turbo: Just Eagle boost Redoer and you're fine lol(I actually came up with this play way way before it got used in the YCS, but whatever) Skull Mesiter is great against this one because the Orcusts banish themselves for cost.  True Sky Strikers: you won't compete against their card advantage, Engage and Widow Anchor. There's nothing worse than facing a complete Sky Striker deck using this one. Unless the player piloting the other is really bad. Since you have yourself a Kagari and you know that there's going to be people playing Strikes on your OTS, or something, just grab yourself 3 GHost Reapers and then use on Kagari, their game is over.  And that's about it. I hope Engage and Widow drops in place so I can play the deck normally :v

deck_excerpt: A constantly up-to-date pure D/D/D deck which focuses on the control aspect of the archetype without sacrificing the combo-oriented playstyle
deck_description:
Hi everyone reading this, I'm Doujinlord, and I've been a dedicated D/D/D player since day 1. I've watched countless deck profiles and have perfected my playstyle with this deck for literally years as of now, and I'm convinced that this version of the deck is one of the most efficient ones to date. It's been somewhat inspired by DDD Dave's list, although he goes for a more control-heavy version of the deck that ends up feeling almost anti-meta, which isn't what I was going for with this list. D/D/D Abyss King Gilgamesh is a much needed breath of fresh air for the archetype, as it helps the deck consolidating the pendulum based playstyle this deck has been relying on ever since links were introduced. This isn't exactly a beginner friendly list, and I wouldn't recomend it to someone who's never played the deck before, but it's a very solid and consistent version of the deck that includes only on the D/D/D archetype without sacrificing its viability. There's a few choices that may look weird or subpar at first, and I'd like to go over them:
  • I play 3 D/D Necro Slime instead of D/D Vice Typhon because it's overall less of a dead card, as it can be normal summoned if needed and it can lead into a Linkuriboh
  • I chose to maindeck Shared Ride specifically for the Sky Striker matchup, which is arguably the hardest one for this deck
  • Wavering Eyes is a generally pretty good card to extend your plays once you're done with Gilgamesh, as it can get you a free D/D Savant Kepler, which potentially means having access to any monster in the deck (because of Dark Contract with the Gate)
  • This deck initially played 3 copies of Solemn Strike, which I replaced with 3 copies of Ultimate Providence as it's an overall more versatile card that also helps with setting up your graveyard
Lastly, the entirety of the side deck should mostly be self explanatory, but if you have any questions or suggestions feel free to dm me, I'll gladly change the list if so required~

deck_excerpt: A Deck Profile for the Archetype "Magical Musket".
deck_description:
What is the Deck based on?

The archetype is based on the German opera "Der Freischütz", written by Carl Maria von Weber and premiered in 1821. According to German folklore, the term "Freischütz" refers to a marksman who made a contract with the devil to obtain seven magic bullets with supernatural accuracy. The first six bullets are subservient to the wielder's control, while the seventh will be in the devil's grip completely. All members of this archetype are based on seven characters from the opera, in addition to sporting names and physical appearances to notable figures of American Western history and lore. Visually, all of them share three design aspects: a demonic-styled weapon, a clawed blue arm holding the weapon, and one or more large, red wings with blue eyes near the joint.

What Does the Deck Do?

This archetype revolves around using their monsters to accumulate their Spells/Traps in order to disrupt almost any moves their opponents may be attempting. All of their monsters can activate their effects when a Spell/Trap is activated in the same column as theirs (including opponent's). In addition, they also allows player to activate "Magical Musket" Spell/Traps from their hand, essentially turning them into hand traps, making their moves harder to predict and protect against. Their monsters all have different effects, ranging from searching ("Caspar"), recycling ("Wild" and "Doc"), advantage generators ("Kidbrave" and "Zakiel"), and even swarming ("Starfire" and "Calamity"). Therefore, it is important to get those monsters onto the field as fast as possible. Since they're all LIGHT Fiends, they can utilize "Ties of the Brethren" as their main card to swarm the field, most of the time to bring out "Caspar", "Doc", and "Kidbrave" for maximum benefits.

Major Weakness/Downfalls

While powerful and consistent with their plethora of monster effects to generate advantage, it is also their greatest weakness. All "Magical Musket" Spells/Traps can only be activated while the player controls a "Magical Musket" monster, limiting their utility. Furthermore, they almost have no means of Special Summoning outside of their own theme (that doesn't rely on monster presence on the field), so any Summon negation cards such as "Forced Back", "Solemn Warning", "Chaos Trap Hole", and "Horn of Heaven" can help slow them down. Because of this Normal Summon dependence, this deck's particularly vulnerable when going second. Hand traps are also effective against this deck, particularly "Effect Veiler", "Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit", "Herald of Orange Light", or "PSY-Framegear Gamma", since they can negate "Magical Musket" monster effects while also being out of reach from negation effect of "Cross-Domination". Mass-removal cards that can avoid "Last Stand" or "Fiendish Deal" are also effective to clear their entire field in one fell swoop, preventing them from activating more "Magical Musket" cards for the rest of that turn.

deck_excerpt: Fun Superheavy Samurai deck for casual play only!
deck_description:
Strategies:
  • Drum: Generic lv. 1 Tuner, can be a good comeback in clutch situations if you just set it ace-down
  • Battleball: Can throw off some big plays of your opponent if you are going second, non-destruction but targeting though, lv. 2 is a very good lv for that
  • Trumpeter: You will only use the special summon effect tbh, just a free tuner to go into synchros
  • Gigagloves: Very underestimated card I  feel, the kind of search is good but the graveyard effect is AMAZING (atk is 0 forever)
  • Soulpiercer: Very versatile, equip it to monters before synchro, summon it and tribute it with soulpeacemaker its just so much search power
  • Big Waraji: Generic free summon, good to go into steam train king
  • Transporter: Another free summon, but you only wanna use his effect on drum, gigagloves, soulpiercer or helper and ONLY if you have enough things to destroy them that turn
  • Magnet: May seem a bit slow for the deck but you have to consider its basically a free feather duster if going into ogre shutendoji
  • Scales: Offers very good recovery, wouldnt use it for plays and keep it on my hand for clutches(except if you are pretty sure you are going to win)
  • Soulshield Wall: The 1200 makes steam train king a 6k beater --> use it on a lower level synchro, negate an attack, go into higher synchro next turn
  • Soulbuster Gauntlet: You wont believe it but this thing OTKs out of freaking nowhere (dont use equip at all)
  • Soulhorns: Another good OTK help, cards like kyubi just reap through your opponents monsters with that thing. Also good free lv 1 to round up some lvs
  • Helper:  First effect is only effective with big boards, second effect can throw off opponents boards heavily (like with ogre shutendoji)
  • Soulclaw: Another special summon to round up levels, makes steam train king a lot easier because his level is awkward for the archetype
  • Soulpeacemaker: Can correct a lot and provide GY setup or searches with e.g. Soulpiercer
  • Steam Train King: The destroy effect is just a worse twin twister but can b deadly if you have the right cards in your hand, second effect basically destroys half of most deck's GY setups
  • Warlord Susanowo: Good to summon if your opponent has staples in his GY like twin twister or idk mirror force if youre playing casually
  • Beast Kyubi: Gets to 5k in no time and it isnt unusual that it reaches 7k, good OTK tool
  • Sarutobi: Good monster to close turn with, quick effect is awkward for the opponent
  • Stealth Ninja: Its just too beefy to not destroy it with card effects, so it will sometimes stay the whole game
  • Ogre shutendoji: Just a feather duster... I mean do I have to say more? Just good, go into higher synchros though, because he will get demolished next turn
In conclusion: OTKs very consistantly, but struggles a lot in link format. Tranporter and Helper are just useless and it hits the deck harder than it really should. The new coming support is neat, so I would look out for that if you wanna build a deck.   I hope you have fun :)

deck_excerpt: Link spam deck that creates advantage easily and has lots of recovery and protection.
deck_description: The main goal of this deck is to simply get as many monsters on the field to go into easy link summons with the Predaplant engine and all the WATER Nimble monsters, Nimble Angler being your main play maker. The whole Extra Deck lineup is there to make your opponent go minus with Akashic Magician and Thousand-Eyes Restrict and to protect yourself and block your opponent with all the Knightmares, Tri-Gate Wizard and the occational Toadally Awesome that can pop out backrow and make you go even in card economy by special summoning another Frog from the GY. Knightmare Unicorn in here mainly to make you extend your plays by drawing 3 cards in one Draw Phase and then goes to the GY to swap onto a Knightmare Gryphon. Binary Sorceress is there if you want to extand your plays but can't go immediatly into a link 3 and her effect can allow you to destroy powerful monsters with weal Knightmare monsters of yours. The safest early play is to go into Knightmare Phenix + Knightmare Cerberus if you can't manage to get more on the field during your first turn to avoid destruction effect and being run over by monsters during the Battle Phase at the same time, to safely extend your plays on your next turn. Don't be afraid to send your link monsters to the GY as you can get them back with Knightmare Corruptor Iblee for farther linking plays or simply get their full benefit back with Monster Reborn and World Legacy Inheritor.   Swap Frog to combo with Nimble Angler and get 3 monsters on the board without normal summoning, to then send Ronintoadin to the GY and get a free +1 after link summoning with Swap Frog. Don't forget that you can ram Nimble Sunfish into the ennemy monsters to send Nimble Angler to the GY and that you can bait a destrution effect with Nimble Mantato get a +1 out of its loss.   3 copies of Knightmare Corruptor Iblee because she usually is the one you normal summon to then go into Knightmare Mermaid, to then use her effect to special summon another one from the deck, which automatically makes you go down to 1 copy of her and you don't want to draw the only two you would have. It can seem bricky but that's more optimal than it seems.   Dot Scraper, Glow-Up Bulb, Nimble Angler, Treeborn Frog and Ronintoadin as discard cost for the Knightmare crads effect (and Foolish Burial targets) to get a free monster on the field.   Predaplant engine to get Instant Fusion (only 2 to avoid briking or rendering the search useless by already having one in hand), then going into Thousand-Eyes Restrict and eventualy into Linkuriboh (only one copy because it can recycle itself with another Thousand-Eyes Restrict).   If your opponent ever co-links and get the effect of your Knightmares, don't forget that Knightmare Unicorn can pop anything easily to break their co-linking and so can Thousand-Eyes Restrict and Akashic Magician (with the right setup). Side deck of Solemns cards is mainly here to ever stop monsters like Castel, The Skyblaster Musketeer from ruining your precious co-linking, if you are aware that your opponent has that kind of removal. Royal Decree and Red Reboot are there to stop Altergeist from blocking your magic cards and completly shutting down your plays. Don't forget to remove Treeborn Frog from your deck if you ever side a trap card. Salvage and Raigeki can be freely swapped with a 3rd Instant Fusion (if the opponent monster are tricky to run over or get rid of) or a 2d Predaplant Darlingtonia Cobra if you're scared of drawing it thus rendeering it useless.

deck_excerpt: Fun, fairly consistent and easy to learn Shark deck updated to February 2019 format :)
deck_description: I used to play a shark deck way back when rescue rabbit was at 1, xyz remora had just been released and link monsters weren't a thing.  I've been tweaking this build for some time, and after having a few successful runs with it against other 'fun' decks, I thought I'd post it for people to enjoy.  I love cards like Nimble Angler for this deck, as you can plus from twin twisters which keeps you a board presence, and in some situations can get you a link monster on the field after clearing back row, which is always a good thing ;)     Feel free to tweak this as you see fit, I love sharks IRL and was so hyped when they became something fun. Great white is the best card ever made.     For anyone wondering about any combos for this deck, my favourite opener that I started with on my last run before uploading was:  Twin Twisters + Nimble Angler + Rescue Rabbit  + XYZ Remora. Twin twisters into the nimble angler (going second ofc) to then drop out 2 mantas and link off into Mermail Abyssalacia. Rescue Rabbit into GODMODE (Great white) to then make the Gem knight Pearl, then use XYZ Remora to make Pearl not consume pointless materials and make Shark Drake. Fifth card in said starting hand was called by the grave..shenanigans.

deck_excerpt: Pure Thunder Dragons 2019 (Post January 2019 Banlist) (Going First)
deck_description: So I know a lot of you guys have probably seen my Top 48 NJ Regional Brilliant Thunder Dragon build and are probably wondering well Eugene, how do we play Pure Thunder Dragons because of the banlist?? well I have the answer for you! After a lot of playtesting, this is what I would be playing for Pure Thunder Dragons to top at an event like a regional or YCS after the most recent January 2019 Banlist. This is a spicy build that I have come up with from scratch like most of my other builds I come up with for you guys. First off, after testing this deck has a pretty low brick rate and most of the time going first, you will be able to end on two Thunder Dragon Colossus and a Thunder Dragon Titan with one or two pops from Titan, or triple Colossus and you may also be able to end on a Number 22: Zombiestein as well. The main combo to end up with this board is a two card combo using Thunder Dragonhawk and Batteryman Solar. You normal summon Solar to use its effect to send Thunder Dragonroar from your deck to graveyard and then use Hawk's effect in hand to special summon Roar from grave. Then go into Some Summer Summoner and use Roar's effect to special summon Thunder Dragondark from the deck and use those three monsters to go into triple Colossus. Two of my spicy cards in the deck are the Lightpulsar Dragon and the Darkflare Dragon. These cards interact really well with the Thunder Dragons because you can banish them to summon these dragons and use the Thunder Dragon monster's effects since they activate when they are banished. Also Lightpulsar is nice because it can be summoned from not only the hand but the graveyard as well by sending a Light and Dark type monsters from your hand to grave. While making the deck I also realized wait, Galaxy-Eyes Photon Dragon can be searched off Melody of The Awakening Dragon. So I added that in because it can come up sometimes as well as with the new link two, Galaxy-Eyes Solflare Dragon from Soul Fusion. I hope you guys enjoy this deck and stick around for more!

Ok. So this was a deck I made way WAY back when. I made it for two reasons, one, I bought the Legendary Dragons box and already had all the foiled versions of the Legendary Knights, before they got stolen, and because I was in a Yu-Gi-Oh roleplay Discord Server, and I used it as a deck for my character. The reason why it's bad? Because I was about 15 at the time, and I was still new to Yu-Gi-Oh. I did, however, saw something I could potentially abuse. The fusion, Buster Blader, the Dragon Destroying Swordsman, gains 1000 attack and defense for each Dragon on your opponent's field and GY, but can't attack directly. I then remember I had a copy of Magnum Sheild and United we stand, and, the deck included Red-Eyes Black Dragon Sword, which equips to a monster and gives it 1000 attack, alongside 500 attack and defense for each dragon on any field and GY. So I got to wondering, what if I got Buster Blader equipped with these cards. Loe and behold, I made a glass cannon. It was clunky and bad, with horrible searching and just mediocre attacks. It was just all around a bad deck. But it was still fun to play.

deck_excerpt: A non-meta Thunder dragon deck that focuses on flexibility and autonomy. Allows for a higher array of plays than your typical hand traps degenerate "m
deck_description: The main purpose of this deck is autonomy. This is not a deck full of degenerate hand traps (You can add them if you wish to make this more "competitive" if you please). This deck is less about stopping your opponent from playing and more about allowing you to consistently make plays.  Fear not fellow Thunder Dragon (TD) users. Even though gold sarcophagus has been limited, we can still abuse the banishment effect of our TDs. This next part will be me explaining the unconventional cards within my build.  Chaos Dragon Levianeer - This is simply a good card. It's destroy effect doesn't target, It is a 3000 attack monster, and it is not hard to summon.  Denko Sekka - This doesn't need much explanation as I have seen other users use Denko in their deck. I honestly feel that it is a stable to have especially when making first turn boards.  Necroface - This is such an underrated card. It was even stronger when gold sarcophagus was at 3. When combined with Allure of darkness, this can give you huge dividents while making your opponent cut out part of their deck. Lastly, if your somehow banishes all of your essential cards, necroface can retrieve them while also gainning attack.  D.D. Sprite / Instant fusion - I put these together because of the potential combo they can complete in tandum. However, they are both still very useful separately. D.D. Sprite can be used to reactivate the effects of thunder dragons that haven't been utilized. Instant fusion can summon Milliennium/Thousand-Eyes restrict that can get rid of a monster from your opponent. It also can be used to summon Invoked Raidjin. Raidjin can then flip itself upside-down and survive instant fusion's effect. When combined, any monster summoned with instant fusion can survive after the turn if D.D. Sprite's effect is used on it.  Selective Reborn - Can be used to banish thunder dragons to utilize their effects while also special summoning one from the graveyard.  Celestial Sextant - This is more of an experimental card. One issue with thunder dragons occurs when you have cards like beastial or avian without anyway of using them. This card is simply more draw power.  Super Polymerization - Combined with Aleister, this can allow for some sneaky plays. I see invokes as the new Shaddolls. No reason not to use Super Poly.  Pot of Acquisitiveness - This is another experimental card. This is a bit of a "win-harder" card, but I find it useful.

deck_excerpt: Bounce everything back and troll your friends!
deck_description: So, with the publishing of Impcantation monsters, I went ahead and threw together a ritual spam deck. But, I didn't know what to make. I could go for Nekroz, but then again I wanted to use Shinobirds as well. Or even use some generic Ritual monsters as well to make a beat down deck. Then I remembered, Impcantations can ritual summon ANY ritual monster, as long as you use their respective spell card. So, with some testing and building, I came up with this, the Shinobird control deck! So, I'll show you what I mean. The Shinobird boss monsters both can return any card to the hand, with the only weakness being cards that resist any other card effects. With up to three non-targeting/destruction, it will almost always go off. So this deck is clearly a go second deck. Of course, you don't have to. What you could do is summon Amorphactor Pain, the Imagination Dracoverlord first, which stops most of your opponent's monsters. (Only cards being Rituals and Links) You can use Amano-Iwato as a Soul Drain with legs, and it doesn't stop Amorphactor Pain as well since it is an effect that doesn't activate. Use Shinobarron and Shinobarroness to get rid of problem cards, and use Impcantation cards to recycle them. If things don't work out, you have two different options. One, use the Mega Monarch to banish itself and send 8 monsters from your extra deck to the grave. Herald of the Light Arc and Elder Entity N'tss to get rid of three cards on your opponent's field, and add three ritual monsters or cards to your hand, then you can send 8 cards from your opponent's extra deck as well! Second, which is most destructive, is using Amaterasu, which can only be set. After being flipped up, it banishes every card on the field with no target. Once again, a powerful card. You shouldn't have that many cards on the field if your getting kinda beat. Use Aratama to find it. Overall, this deck is fun to mess around and to make shenanigans with. Try it out at your locals today!

deck_description: Not competitive but fun to play

So we all know about the meta deck, Danger! Dark World! But do you know about the duel terminal deck Fabled? Well, I do, and I love it. Fabled Leviathan is best waifu. It works like Dark World, with having advantages of discard, but runs on the spam synchro format. Unfortunately, you can minus real hard so, be careful. You can find yourself empty handed quite quick and with a bad defense if you don't play it right. Of course, when you do play it right, it normally ends up with an OTK. I play a Synchro heavy variant, and there is also a link heavy variant. You can, however, play a combo of both, which is shown today. This deck ultimately works like Danger Dark World, but with more synchro monsters and link monster. So instead, I'll give some tips on how to use this deck. 1: Don't get rid of Fabled Grimo or Krus. These two cards are good for extending plays. Grimo can discard itself to add any Fabled monster to your hand, while Krus can revive a level 4 or lower Fabled in your GY. It's hard to do anything if you have these in your hand first turn, but later on, it helps a lot. 2: Fabled Dianaira, use him. Despite it being a very simple effect, it is very useful. It stops your opponent's first normal spell card, which can go a long way. And don't worry about the tribute cost, I mean. If you can't tribute summon this monster, then, you might as well not play this game anymore. 3: Improve on this deck This deck is just a skeleton. It's meant to get an understanding on to how the deck should work, and it is not a final. Make it your own way, make it some, Quasar spam build or even a Fabled Dark World build! The possibilities are endless.

Alito is a character appearing in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ZEXAL anime. He is an Emperor from the Barian World, working to gather the "Numbers" to prevent his world's destruction.[5] Contrary to his mission, Alito became a friendly rival of Yuma Tsukumo's at one point. Alito uses a "Battlin' Boxer" Deck, utilizing various cards to swarm the field such as "Battlin' Boxer Sparrer" and "Ring Announcer" for Xyz Summons and others to negate Trap Cards such as "Counter Clash" and "Fancy Footwork". He also uses several cards devoted to detaching Overlay Units such as "Overlay Flash" and "Xyz Block", primarily to power up his "Battlin' Boxer Lead Yoke". During his Tag-Team Duel with Nistro, he focuses on a more defensive approach, while letting Nistro take the risks of using "Number 54: Lion Heart". Here, he uses Level 3 "Battlin' Boxer" monsters named after illegal boxing maneuvers, while his "Battlin' Boxer Cheat Commissioner" Xyz Monster is based on corrupt boxing manager, reflecting how he used Nistro. Alito later gains the ability to perform a Chaos Draw, giving him access to "Rank-Up-Magic - The Seventh One", allowing him to easily Special Summon his "Number C105: Battlin' Boxer Comet Cestus", which he later augments with "Number 80: Rhapsody in Berserk" and "Number C80: Requiem in Berserk". Pendulum Monster

Pendulum Monster (Japanese: ペンデュラムモンスター Pendyuramu Monsutā; usually abbreviated Ｐ（ペンデュラム）モンスター), also called a Pendulum Card in the early episodes of the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime, is a type of Monster Card that is half green. They first appeared in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime, and were introduced to the OCG and TCG in Starter Deck 2014 and Super Starter: Space-Time Showdown respectively. In addition to normal usages, a Pendulum Monster can also be activated from the hand as a Spell Card in a Pendulum Zone; if there are Pendulum Monsters in both Pendulum Zones, the player can perform a Pendulum Summon. So far, Normal, Effect, Fusion, Synchro and Xyz Pendulum Monsters have been seen. Pendulum Monsters can also be Tuner, Flip and Spirit monsters.

Pendulum Scale

 

  A Pendulum Scale (Japanese:Pendyuramu Sukēru, abbreviated in card text) (abbreviated as "PS" or "PSC" in the manga) is a set of indicators unique to Pendulum Monsters. Two of them are located above the "Monster Effect" text box of the Pendulum Monster, with the "Pendulum Effect" of the Pendulum Monster placed between them. All Pendulum Monsters have two Pendulum Scale values, signified by the blue symbol for the left, and the red symbol for the right.

this deck is plane and simple, you use the level 4 monsters to link/xyz summon into utopia and any other monster in the extra deck. the best combo is to

deck_excerpt: A D/D/D deck made for the link format
deck_description: This is an aggro deck that focuses on swarming the field. It can perform many combos and never bricks. D/D savant Copernicus This card is the decks' main combo starter and is extremely flexible. If you draw this card on your first turn and one other D/D card you can combo into either a zefra metaltron or a D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh. The first combo ends with D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh a full scale and the D/D savant copernicus on the field. Start by normal summoning D/D savant copernicus and use its effect to send D/D swirl slime to the graveyard then banish it and special summon any D/D monster from your hand. Use both D/D monsters on the field to go into D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh and activate his effect to set a pendulum scale. I usually use D/D/D destiny king zero larplace and D/D savant newton. You can then pendulum summon the D/D savant copernicus back from the extra deck as well as any other D/D monsters in your hand.  The second combo requires you to start with D/D savant copernicus and one other D/D monster or dark contract in hand. Normal summon D/D savant copernicus and send D/D lamia to the graveyard. Then use D/D lamia's effect to special summon itself from the graveyard. Using both monsters go into crystron needlefiber using his effect special summon a second copy of D/D lamia from your deck. Using this D/D lamia go into Linkuriboh, then using both crystron needlefiber and Linkuriboh as materials special summon zefra metaltron. D/D swirl slime D/D swirl slime is one of the best combo starters in the deck as it gets you two monsters on the field for the cost of two monsters in hand. Usually, when you start with swirl slime you fusion summon straight into D/D/D flame king genghis or D/D/D flame king high genghis and then special summon another monster straight out of your hand. This card is usually the target for cards like foolish burial and D/D savant copernicus because it can special summon any D/D monster from your hand. D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh I usually try to make this card on my first turn to set my pendulum scales. After this the card kind of just sits there the best thing to do after you summon D/D/D abyss king gilgamesh is let your opponent destroy it this lets you special summon a D/D monster from your extra deck or graveyard in defence position ignoring it's summoning conditions. I usually special summon D/D/D super doom king bright armageddon off of this effect as it stops your opponent from being able to disassemble your board with it's protection effect also it's high stat line usually means your opponent won't be able to destroy it by battle.

Yugo

Yugo, spelled Hugo (Yūgo) in the Japanese version, is a character in the Yu-Gi-Oh! ARC-V anime. He is the Synchro Dimension counterpart of Yuya Sakaki (Standard Dimension), Yuri (Fusion Dimension) and Yuto (Xyz Dimension), and one of Z-ARC's reincarnations. Yugo is a Turbo Duelist and was mistakenly notorious among members of the Resistance as a "Fusion follower" ("minion" in the Japanese version) mostly due to his name sounding similar to the Japanese word for "Fusion". Yugo is persistently in pursuit of Yuri, however, due to confusions of their similar faces and misunderstandings, he initially chased after Yuto in search of Rin, only to be informed of his mistake by Zuzu Boyle.

deck_excerpt: Trickstar OTK Synchro Turbo (Going First or Second)
deck_description: I know its been a while since I've posted a new deck but I've been testing for you guys for some really cool spicy decks and I wanted my other decks to get more views and kinda sink in. I like to give decks time and then post a new one so everyone has a chance to check it out! Anyways I was looking at Destrudo The Lost Dragon's Frisson and was thinking if there's anything cool to do with him since he's a really good synchro turbo card and then I saw Shooting Riser Dragon which is a level 7 tuner that can synchro summon during your opponent's turn. I saw that and noticed how it's effect says it can reduce its own level by a monster you send from deck to grave and realized you can use that plus another monster to make Black Rose Dragon during your opponent's turn to blow up their field which is pretty crazy. Anyways, this deck can go first or second it doesn't really matter. Going first you have many tools at your disposal like the Black Rose Dragon play I just explained and triple Trickstar Reincarnation as well as the three Solemns. Going second you can make Yazi, Evil of The Yang Zing with Destrudo and a Trickstar monster and summon Mare Mare and go into Borrelsword Dragon to OTK. I wanted to make a Trickstar deck that can go either first or second that is pretty consistent for you guys. I know you guys like my other Trickstar decks but I'm hoping you guys will love this one. The reason for Hack Worm is for the Destrudo Shooting Riser Dragon play I explained in the beginning. It's a free monster to special summon going first that allows you to use for Shooting Riser Dragon after you go through your Trickstar cards in hand. Another way to bring out Black Rose Dragon without Hack Worm is by using Trickstar Reincarnation in your graveyard during your opponent's main phase 1 to special summon a Trickstar monster from grave and then Shooting Riser Dragon and that Trickstar monster to synchro into Black Rose Dragon. I really hope you guys enjoy this deck and stick around for new decks weekly.

deck_excerpt: One-card True King of All Calamities using Orcusts.
deck_description:
The goal of this Deck is to turbo out The True King of All Calamities using The Phantom Knight's Rank Up-Magic. Preferably using Destroymare Iblee to Link Summon into Troymare Mermaid for a 1 card combo True King of all Calamities. However, this Deck is susceptible to many hand traps, potentially ending your combos. At the start of the game, utilize your many Turbo cards to Link Summon into Troymare Mermaid. After that, you can follow these steps for an easy combo:
  • On summon, activate Troymare Mermaid's effect to discard 1 card; Special Summon Orphegel Troymare
  • Link Summon Orphegel Galatea using Troymare Mermaid and Orphegel Troymare
  • In the GY, use Orphegel Troymare's effect to banish itself and send Orphegel Diver to the GY
  • In the GY, activate Orphegel Diver's effect to banish itself and Special Summon Orphegel Scherzone
  • Activate Orphegel Galatea's effect to shuffle 1 banished Machine-Type monsters and set Orphegel Babel
  • Using Orphegel Galatea and Orphegel Scherzone, Link Summon into The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche
  • Activate The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche's effect to send The Phantom Knight's Silent Boots to the GY, then set Phantom Knight's Fog Blade
  • In the GY, activate The Phantom Knight's Silent Boots to banish itself and add The Phantom Knights' Rank Up-Magic Launch
  • In the GY, activate Orphegel Scherzone to banish itself and Special Summon Orphegel Galatea from the GY
  • Using Orphegel Galatea as Overlay Material, Xyz Summon Sheorphegel Dingirsu to a zone The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche points to
  • On Sheorphegel Dingirsu's summon (DO NOT ACTIVATE HIS EFFECT), The Phantom Knights of Rusty Bardiche will activate to target and destroy 1 card on the field.
  • Target Sheorphegel Dingirsu, but detach one Xyz Material to prevent it's destruction
  • Activate The Phantom Knights' Rank Up-Magic Launch to Xyz Summon The True King of All Calamities using Sheorphegel Dingirsu

deck_excerpt: A Synchro WATER based deck revolving around the White Aura monsters.
deck_description: In my quest to create a new The Legendary Fisherman III deck I ended up just making a bit of a Synchro WATER deck. It's not great, there isn't any really strong win condition of the deck. It mainly revolves around the White Aura monsters and flooding the field a bit.   Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince can easily discard a Atlantean Dragoons to then do a few things. You can pull a Lappis Dragon to have it immediately summon or you can do what I prefer and pull another copy of Atlantean Dragoons and then use Mermail Abyssmegalo to discard that copy (and then pull a Lappis Dragon). The Legendary Fisherman III is a great card if you can get it out but don't bank on it. Instead try to use it with Tatsunoko to summon White Aura Bihamut. Crystron Needlefiber can use his effect to summon either Coral Dragon or Ib the World Chalice Miko (which can then pull World Legacy Succession). One for One usually goes int Neptabyss, the Atlantean Prince. I really like Sea Stealth Attack since it got released but I've found myself struggling to get it out with A Legendary Ocean. Plenty of work can be done to improve this but I am currently releasing it as is!

deck_excerpt: Graydle Control with brand new playstyle!
deck_description:
Use your Graydle monster and other Tuner to keep Link and Synchro Summon monsters for OTK. There are 3 main strategies for this build:
  • Control: Using Graydle monsters to attack your opponent monsters, take some battle damage, then control your opponent, then use them to attack again. (Don't do this against unaffected/cannot be targeted monsters, because you can't control them)
 
  • OTK: By continuously using monsters to Link Summon, then activate Graydle Slime monster to destroy Graydle Dragon and a Graydle card, so you can Synchro Summon 2 monster Level 8 Synchro Monster (usually Graydle Dragon and Stardust Dragon) then attack your opponent.
 
  • Field Lock: Using multiple Graydle monsters (especially Graydle Slime Jr.) to protect you from attack, then control monsters your opponent control (in case you have lack of monsters, activate Graydle Parasite for more), then after a few turns, when you have enough card(s) for a combo, you should use monsters you have to Link Summon then OTK your opponent.
Please comment below if you have any questions, and if you like this, give a thumb up!
